solutions.content:
# Approach 1: math, just divide as long as possible
We just divide with each factor as long as this is possible and if only one remains the number is ugly.

```cpp
    static bool isUgly(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) return false;

        while (n % 2 == 0) n /= 2;
        while (n % 3 == 0) n /= 3;
        while (n % 5 == 0) n /= 5;
        return n == 1;
    }
```

If we want to do something slighlty more generic, we could do something like this:

```cpp
    static bool isUgly(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) return false;

        for (const int d : {2, 3, 5})
            while (n % d == 0) n /= d;

        return n == 1;
    }
```

In case you are wondering if you should be using bit masking and shifting for the "divisible by 2" test and write code like this:

```cpp
    static bool isUgly(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) return false;

        while ((n & 1) == 0) n >>=1;
        while (n % 3 == 0) n /= 3;
        while (n % 5 == 0) n /= 5;
        return n == 1;
    }
```

Looks like clang is smart enough to see through this and generate the same code: https://godbolt.org/z/YhTEYeMre -- and FWIW the generated assemble doesn't look like at all to what I expected, e.g. the generated code doesn't have a single "div" instruction.

**Complexity Analysis**
  * Time Complexity: $$O(\log n)$$
  * Space Complexity: $$O(1)$$

