# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Every ugly number can be expressed in the form of 2, 3 and 5 in varying powers. Hence, if a number can be expressed using only by 2, 3 and 5, we can call it an ugly number.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
First, we check if a given number is divisible by 2 and then continue dividing it by 2 till its no longer divisible by it. Then, we repeat the process for 3 and 5.

Lastly, if we are left with 1, then the given number is an ugly number.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
**NOTE:** Time complexity would be constant as the greatest possible input that can be given is 2^31-1 and this number will iterate only the first loop and that too just 31 times.

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isUgly(int n) {
        if(!n) return false;

        while(!(n%2))
            n/=2;

        while(!(n%3))
            n/=3;

        while(!(n%5))
            n/=5;

        if(n==1) return true;
        return false;
    }
};
```

